Canadian courts martial cannot try anyone for murder, manslaughter or
abductions of persons under the age of 16 within Canada (it used to be
&quot;murder, treason or rape&quot;)
http://www.admfincs.forces.gc.ca/qr_o/vol2/ch102_e.asp#102.23 . Outside of
Canada, they can try such offences, and not just by members of the CF, but
also by anyone deemed to be accompanying the CF -- this was a bit of a shock
to the parliamentarians I took to South West Asia who thought themselves
covered by the privileges of the House of Commons. When the charge is laid by
a civil authority in Canada, the member is handed over for trial. In Germany,
the Netherlands, Belgium, the U.K. and the U.S., about the only places other
than SWA that Canada has folks stationed, civil offences by members are tried
by the local courts. CF members on exchange are also subject to the
disciplinary code of the force with which they serve.

People sentenced to two years or longer are sent to a penitentiary for the
first day of the third year (time in the CF's digger is considered hard labour
and counts more than day-for-day toward eligibility for parole).

CF member who axes co-eds in Canada will be handed over to province or
territory authorities for trial; overseas, he may be tried by civil authority.
In a place like the 'Stan where our confidence in the local justice system is
not bolstered by an SoFA, he gets tried by GCM and, if found guilty, goes to
the SPDB for two years, less a day, and thence to Bowesville for the balance
of his incarceration.
