'A couple hundred years ago', the Royal Navy was a merit-based organisation-
albeit  a friend in high places could assist  in gaining _appointments_.
There were really only three ranks of officer grades; Lieutenants, Captains
with Admirals above them.  Lieutenants needed to pass an examination and
those successful would be styled 'Passed Lieutenants' and then appointed to
ships, for commission,  and hopefully gain a more advantageous appointment
following that commission.
Effectively they'd start as  (say) a Sixth Lieutenant on a big ship then
eventually a First Lieutenant on a small ship becoming a First Lieutenant on
a really big ship.  Seniority was based on the date of 'Passed Lieutenant'.
Eventually a Lieutenant would be become a Captain and so 'Posted'. With a
fair wind, ... and a bloody war ....the Most senior Post Captain would
become the most junior Admiral.

A prerequisite for candidates for the Lieutenants examination was the
accumulation of an amount of 'sea-time'. In olden-times without a
centralised registry; the word (written) of ship's captains was considered
sufficient; Captains were entitled to have servants; cooks, coxswains,
secretary etc. etc. and many Captains entered on to their ship's muster
rolls the names of sons/nephews/wards etc. . This enabled the boys to
accumulate sea-time (ashore).

Midshipmen were neither officers (who slept aft) nor crew (who slept
for'ard) but were youths who were studying to 'learn  the trade' and sit
their examination for 'Lieutenant's some of these youths may have
accumulated 'sea-time' prior to being accepted for a midshipmen's berth on a
Captain's ship. . When midshipmen were performing on-board roles, it was
considered as 'on-job-training'

[A parallel path existed for _Mates_ , who acted as assistant to the ship's
complement of $Trade Masters.] A 'Mate' could become a candidate alongside
midshipmen for the Lieutenancy examinations.

